# TypeScript, Lint, and Naming

- Follow the existing ESLint configs. Run the package lint command or targeted `eslint --fix` after touching imports.
- Use TypeScript for all app and package code. Prefer explicit exported interfaces/types for shared package APIs.
- Use `camelCase` for variables/functions, `PascalCase` for classes/types/enums, and `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` only for true constants.
- File names use kebab-case for multi-word utility files, components, services, and rules.
- Prefer type-only imports where useful, but do not fight the local ESLint config.
- Keep imports sorted. Server lint enforces `simple-import-sort` for imports and exports.
- Avoid `any` in new shared APIs. It is tolerated in legacy app code only when matching existing patterns.
- Keep functions small and pure where possible; move reusable pure logic to `@333fm/utils`.
